==Old English==
===Etymology===
From West Germanic ''*hof'', from Indo-European ''*keup-'', a suffixed form of ''*keu-'' ‘bend, cove, hollow’.  Cognate with Old Saxon ''hof'' (Dutch ''hof''), Old High German ''hof'' (German [[Hof]] ‘courtyard’), Old Norse ''hof'' ‘temple’ (Norwegian [[hov]] ‘hill’).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /hof/

===Noun===
'''hof''' {{n}} ({{p}} '''hofu''')

# a [[house]], a [[hall]] or [[building]]
#:''he gewat from his agenum hofe isaac lædan'': he went from his own house leading Isaac.  (''Genesis'')

